initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: Optical neural networks (ONNs) have the potential to accelerate deep learning tasks due to their high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost. In traditional ONNs, light amplitudes are modulated at the input and detected at the output, while light phases are often overlooked despite their potential for carrying information. To tackle this issue, we introduce a new framework called OplixNet that compresses ONNs by utilizing both amplitude and phase components of light signals when modulating input image data. This framework redesigns the input and output sections of ONNs to make optimal use of amplitude and phase information, while also incorporating mutual learning across different ONN structures to maintain accuracy. Experimental results show that OplixNet significantly reduces ONN areas while keeping accuracy within an acceptable range. For instance, a 75.03% area reduction is achieved with only a 0.33% accuracy decrease on a fully connected neural network (FCNN), and a 74.88% area reduction is achieved with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) have the potential to accelerate deep learning tasks due to their high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost. In traditional ONNs, light amplitudes are modulated at the input and detected at the output, while light phases are often overlooked despite their potential for carrying information. To address this issue, a new framework called OplixNet is introduced. OplixNet compresses ONNs by utilizing both amplitude and phase components of light signals when modulating input image data. This framework redesigns the input and output sections of ONNs to optimize the use of amplitude and phase information, and incorporates mutual learning across different ONN structures to maintain accuracy. Experimental results demonstrate that OplixNet significantly reduces ONN areas while maintaining accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, a 75.03% area reduction is achieved with only a 0.33% accuracy decrease on a fully connected neural network (FCNN), and a 74.88% area reduction is achieved with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) can speed up deep learning tasks with their fast performance, high throughput, and low energy consumption. While traditional ONNs focus on modulating light amplitudes at the input and detecting them at the output, the potential of using light phases for information transmission is often overlooked. To overcome this limitation, a new framework called OplixNet is introduced. OplixNet enhances ONNs by incorporating both amplitude and phase aspects of light signals when processing input image data. This framework optimizes the utilization of amplitude and phase information in the input and output sections of ONNs and promotes mutual learning among different ONN structures to ensure accuracy. Experimental results show that OplixNet significantly reduces the area of ONNs while maintaining accuracy at an acceptable level. For instance, a 75.03% reduction in area is achieved with only a 0.33% decrease in accuracy for a fully connected neural network (FCNN), and a 74.88% reduction in area is achieved with a 2.38% decrease in accuracy for ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) can enhance deep learning tasks by providing rapid performance, high throughput, and minimal energy consumption. While traditional ONNs primarily manipulate light amplitudes at the input and detect them at the output, the use of light phases for data transmission is often overlooked. To address this issue, a new framework called OplixNet has been introduced. OplixNet improves ONNs by integrating both amplitude and phase components of light signals when processing input image data. This framework optimizes the utilization of amplitude and phase information in the input and output stages of ONNs and promotes collaborative learning among different ONN structures to ensure accuracy. Experimental results demonstrate that OplixNet significantly reduces the size of ONNs while maintaining accuracy at an acceptable level. For example, OplixNet achieves a 75.03% reduction in area for a fully connected neural network (FCNN) with only a 0.33% decrease in accuracy, and a 74.88% reduction in area for ResNet-32 with a 2.38% decrease in accuracy.
